<methodology slug="performance-architecture">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>dev</group>
    <domain>software-architect</domain>
    <summary>Design systems to meet explicit SLO targets (p50/p95/p99, throughput, error rate, availability) by addressing all five layers with a measurement-first loop.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>performance</tag>
      <tag>slo</tag>
      <tag>scalability</tag>
      <tag>load-testing</tag>
      <tag>optimization</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-29</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Performance Architecture</title>
    <summary>Design systems to meet explicit SLO targets (p50/p95/p99, throughput, error rate, availability) by addressing all five layers: client, CDN/edge, load balancer, application, and data. Run a measurement-first loop: profiler agent reads APM/traces → analyzer identifies bottleneck layer → designer proposes change with predicted p95 improvement → validator runs a load test that proves or disproves the prediction. Never optimize without a captured baseline.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Performance problems are layer-specific: a missing index looks identical to a connection-pool exhaustion in aggregate metrics. Without layer attribution, agents rewrite cold code paths because they look messy, not because they are hot. SLOs from user-impact analysis (not industry tables) give falsifiable targets; p99 is where users churn, not mean latency.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Defining SLOs and error budgets at design time, before performance becomes a customer complaint.</item>
        <item>Pre-launch capacity planning for a feature expected to receive measurable traffic.</item>
        <item>Performance regression triage: structured layer-by-layer narrowing.</item>
        <item>Cost optimization driven by tail latency or compute waste.</item>
        <item>Pre-IPO/audit scenarios requiring documented performance commitments.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Pure prototypes — premature optimization slows delivery without buying reliability.</item>
        <item>Pages/APIs with no production traffic yet — measure first.</item>
        <item>Hot-fixing a single slow query — use profiling tools directly, not a full architecture loop.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="slos-and-layers">
      <rule>
        <statement>Define SLOs from user-impact analysis, not from industry tables. "p95 &lt; 200ms" is a textbook number; the real target comes from measuring at what latency users abandon the page or the transaction.</statement>
        <rationale>LLM-suggested SLOs consistently default to textbook values; teams then optimize to the wrong target. Tie SLOs to user-journey data and competitive benchmarks.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Startup/MVP: p50 &lt; 200ms, p95 &lt; 500ms, p99 &lt; 2s, throughput &gt; 1k RPS, error rate &lt; 1%, availability 99.9% (43.8 min/month downtime).</item>
        <item>Growth: p50 &lt; 100ms, p95 &lt; 300ms, p99 &lt; 1s, throughput &gt; 10k RPS, error rate &lt; 0.1%, availability 99.95% (21.9 min/month).</item>
        <item>Enterprise: p50 &lt; 50ms, p95 &lt; 150ms, p99 &lt; 500ms, throughput &gt; 100k RPS, error rate &lt; 0.01%, availability 99.99% (4.4 min/month).</item>
      </list>
      <note>p99 is where users churn, not mean latency. Always report p95 and p99 together; mean latency is a vanity metric for performance work.</note>
      <rule>
        <statement>Attribute the bottleneck to exactly one layer before proposing a fix. "The system is slow" is not actionable; "DB query p95 is 180ms, consuming 60% of the request budget" is.</statement>
        <rationale>Layer-agnostic optimizations waste effort — agents rewrite cold code paths because they look messy, not because they are hot. APM traces give layer attribution; flame graphs give code attribution within a layer.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Layer 1 — CLIENT: browser rendering, JS bundle execution, network RTT. Target: First Contentful Paint &lt; 1.5s, Time to Interactive &lt; 3s. Tools: Lighthouse, WebVitals, bundle analyzer.</item>
        <item>Layer 2 — EDGE/CDN: static assets, edge caching, compression, edge functions. Target: cache hit ratio &gt; 95%, edge latency &lt; 50ms globally. Tools: Cloudflare Analytics, CloudFront metrics.</item>
        <item>Layer 3 — LOAD BALANCER: request distribution, health checks, SSL termination. Target: connection overhead &lt; 5ms. Tools: nginx/HAProxy metrics, connection pool saturation alerts.</item>
        <item>Layer 4 — APPLICATION: code efficiency, concurrency model, async processing, algorithm complexity. Target: request processing &lt; 100ms (excluding I/O wait). Tools: py-spy, async-profiler, distributed traces.</item>
        <item>Layer 5 — DATA: query optimization, indexing, connection pooling, cache hit ratio. Target: DB query p95 &lt; 50ms, cache hit ratio &gt; 85%. Tools: pg_stat_statements, EXPLAIN ANALYZE, pgBadger, RedisInsight.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="error-budget">
      <list>
        <item>99.9% availability = 43.8 minutes downtime per month, 8.7 hours per year.</item>
        <item>99.95% availability = 21.9 minutes per month, 4.4 hours per year.</item>
        <item>99.99% availability = 4.4 minutes per month, 52.6 minutes per year.</item>
        <item>Error budget = (1 - SLO) × period_duration. Burn through budget faster than the period → freeze feature releases, prioritize reliability work.</item>
      </list>
      <rule>
        <statement>Alert on error budget burn rate, not raw availability. A 6x burn rate with 72h remaining in the month demands immediate response; a 1x burn rate is within expectations.</statement>
        <rationale>Raw availability percentages update too slowly; burn rate gives early warning before the budget is exhausted.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="capacity-planning">
      <list>
        <item>Peak RPS = (peak_concurrent_users × requests_per_user_per_minute) / 60.</item>
        <item>Design target = peak_RPS × 2 (headroom) × 1.5 (growth buffer) = 3× peak.</item>
        <item>Instance count = design_target_RPS / single_instance_capacity_RPS, rounded up + 1 for N+1 redundancy.</item>
        <item>Connection pool size = (core_count × 2) + effective_spindle_count. For SSDs: core_count × 2, typically 10–50 connections per app instance.</item>
      </list>
      <example type="good" title="Capacity calculation">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
Peak concurrent users: 100,000
Requests per user per minute: 10
Peak RPS = 100,000 * 10 / 60 = 16,667

Design target (3x): 50,000 RPS
Single instance capacity: 500 RPS
Required instances: 50,000 / 500 = 100
With N+1 redundancy: 101
With 50% headroom: 150 instances
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="scalability">
      <list>
        <item>Horizontal (scale out): add instances. Limit: near-infinite. Downtime: zero. Complexity: higher (stateless design, service discovery required). Cost: linear. Best for: web APIs, stateless services.</item>
        <item>Vertical (scale up): increase CPU/RAM per instance. Limit: hardware ceiling. Downtime: usually required. Complexity: lower. Cost: exponential at high tiers. Best for: databases, legacy apps, stateful services.</item>
      </list>
      <rule>
        <statement>Horizontal scaling requires stateless application design: sessions externalized to Redis, no in-process shared mutable state, no local file writes for shared data.</statement>
        <rationale>Horizontal scaling breaks sticky assumptions — any instance can receive any request. In-process state becomes a consistency bug, not just a performance issue.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Horizontal sharding: route by key range or hash. Example: users A-M → shard 1, users N-Z → shard 2. Pro: write throughput scales linearly. Con: cross-shard queries are expensive.</item>
        <item>Vertical partitioning: split by domain. Example: user profiles → Users DB, orders → Orders DB, analytics → ClickHouse. Pro: each store optimized for its access pattern. Con: cross-domain joins require application-layer merging.</item>
        <item>HPA scales pods based on CPU, memory, or custom metrics (via KEDA for queue depth, RPS, etc.).</item>
        <item>K8s 1.33+: configurable tolerance for scale-up and scale-down decisions — prevents oscillation on noisy metrics.</item>
        <item>Combine HPA with Cluster Autoscaler for infrastructure scaling; HPA handles pod count, Cluster Autoscaler handles node count.</item>
        <item>Cost savings: 50-70% with well-tuned autoscaling vs always-on over-provisioned cluster.</item>
        <item>Cold-start latency is the key risk: if pod startup takes 30s, a spike can exhaust capacity before scale-out completes. Pre-scale before known traffic events.</item>
      </list>
      <rule>
        <statement>Never set connection pool size equal to the number of concurrent request handlers (threads or async tasks). The pool interacts with the DB thread count, not the app concurrency.</statement>
        <rationale>An oversized pool exhausts DB connection slots; an undersized pool queues requests behind pool acquisition. Use the empirical formula: (core_count × 2) + spindles.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Formula: pool_size = (core_count × 2) + effective_spindle_count.</item>
        <item>For SSDs (spindles ≈ 1): pool_size = core_count × 2. Typical result: 10–50 connections per app instance.</item>
        <item>PgBouncer (PostgreSQL): transaction-mode pooling; one DB connection serves N app clients in round-robin. Use when app connection count exceeds DB max_connections.</item>
        <item>ProxySQL (MySQL): connection multiplexing with query routing rules for read/write splitting.</item>
        <item>SQLAlchemy (Python): pool_size (persistent) + max_overflow (burst headroom). Set pool_timeout to fail fast rather than queue indefinitely.</item>
      </list>
      <rule>
        <statement>Move any operation taking &gt; 200ms off the synchronous request path. Return 202 Accepted immediately, enqueue the work, notify via webhook or polling endpoint.</statement>
        <rationale>Long-synchronous paths block server threads, inflate p99 latency, and cause cascading timeouts at the caller. Async decoupling is the fix, not increasing thread pool size.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Background jobs pattern: HTTP → API → 202 Accepted → Queue → Worker → heavy processing → notify. Use Celery (Python), BullMQ (Node), Sidekiq (Ruby).</item>
        <item>Batch writes: replace N individual DB inserts in a loop with bulk_insert / COPY for N rows. 10-100x throughput improvement for large datasets.</item>
        <item>Message queue selection: Kafka for event replay + ordered streams; RabbitMQ for complex routing + RPC; Redis Streams for simple queues + low latency (&lt;1ms); SQS/Service Bus for serverless cloud-native.</item>
        <item>Streaming processing (Flink, Spark Streaming): for real-time aggregations over high-volume event streams. Use only when the processing graph exceeds what a simple consumer can handle.</item>
      </list>
      <example type="bad" title="N individual inserts">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
# Bad: N database calls in a loop
for item in items:
    db.insert(item)   # 1000 items = 1000 round-trips

# Good: single batch call
db.bulk_insert(items)  # 1000 items = 1 round-trip
        ]]></code>
        <note>Replace per-item inserts with bulk_insert — 10-100x throughput improvement for large datasets.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="database-and-cdn">
      <rule>
        <statement>Never apply functions to indexed columns in WHERE clauses — the optimizer cannot use the index and falls back to a full table scan.</statement>
        <rationale>YEAR(created_at) = 2024 touches every row; created_at &gt;= '2024-01-01' AND created_at &lt; '2025-01-01' uses the B-tree index. This is the single most common avoidable performance regression.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Avoid: SELECT * — fetches all columns including BLOBs, unused JSON, and large text. Always enumerate required columns.</item>
        <item>Avoid: N+1 queries — 1 list query + N detail queries. Fix with eager loading (JOIN or SELECT IN for the foreign key set).</item>
        <item>Use EXPLAIN ANALYZE before and after every index addition to verify the planner uses the new index.</item>
        <item>Partial indexes: CREATE INDEX ON orders (user_id) WHERE status = 'pending' — much smaller than a full index when the filtered set is small.</item>
        <item>Covering indexes: include all columns referenced by a query so the planner can satisfy the query from the index alone without a heap lookup.</item>
        <item>B-tree (default): equality and range queries on scalar types. CREATE INDEX idx_name ON table(col).</item>
        <item>Hash: equality only, slightly smaller than B-tree. CREATE INDEX USING hash. Rarely worth the trade-off — B-tree handles equality fine.</item>
        <item>GIN: arrays, JSONB keys, full-text search. CREATE INDEX USING gin(col). Required for @&gt; (contains) and @@ (text search) operators.</item>
        <item>GiST: geometric types, range types, nearest-neighbor search. CREATE INDEX USING gist. Used with PostGIS and range overlap queries.</item>
        <item>BRIN: large, append-only tables sorted by a physical attribute (timestamps on time-series). Very small index, effective only when physical and logical order correlate.</item>
      </list>
      <rule>
        <statement>Index columns in WHERE, JOIN ON, and ORDER BY clauses. Always index foreign keys on the child table to avoid sequential scans during JOINs.</statement>
        <rationale>Un-indexed foreign keys cause full table scans on every JOIN and ON DELETE CASCADE operation — invisible in dev at small data sizes, catastrophic at production scale.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Kafka: 500k+ msg/sec, 2–8ms latency. Best for event streaming, log aggregation, audit trail, event replay, multi-consumer fan-out. Con: operational complexity, minimum cluster is 3 brokers.</item>
        <item>RabbitMQ: 25k msg/sec, 1–5ms latency. Best for complex routing (topic exchanges, dead-letter queues), RPC patterns, priority queues. Con: no event replay, messages are consumed and gone.</item>
        <item>Redis Streams: 100k msg/sec, &lt;1ms latency. Best for simple queues, real-time notifications, lightweight fan-out. Con: limited durability without AOF, no complex routing.</item>
        <item>SQS / Azure Service Bus: variable, 10–50ms latency. Best for serverless, cloud-native, managed scaling. Con: higher latency, vendor lock-in.</item>
        <item>Cloudflare Workers: &lt;1ms cold start, 330+ cities. Best for edge logic, A/B testing, personalized routing, auth checks at edge.</item>
        <item>Vercel Edge Functions: &lt;5ms cold start, 100+ regions. Best for Next.js / React apps, middleware-style request transforms.</item>
        <item>AWS Lambda@Edge: 50–200ms cold start. Best for AWS-native workloads requiring CloudFront integration.</item>
        <item>Fastly Compute: &lt;10ms cold start, 90+ PoPs. Best for high-throughput APIs requiring real-time cache purge.</item>
      </list>
      <rule>
        <statement>Do not use edge functions for database-heavy operations (&gt;2 queries), CPU-intensive tasks, or complex orchestration workflows. Edge runtimes have strict memory and CPU time limits.</statement>
        <rationale>Edge functions are optimized for fast network-level decisions (routing, auth header injection, A/B flag reads), not for application logic that belongs in the origin API.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Minification: 30–50% size reduction for JS/CSS. Tools: esbuild (fastest), Terser (JS), cssnano (CSS).</item>
        <item>Compression: Brotli achieves 70–90% size reduction vs uncompressed; 15–20% better than gzip. Enable at CDN and origin.</item>
        <item>Image optimization: WebP is 25–35% smaller than JPEG at equivalent quality. Use Cloudinary, imgproxy, or Next.js Image for on-the-fly conversion and responsive srcset.</item>
        <item>Bundle splitting: split by route or component so users only load code for the current page. Webpack, Vite, and Rollup all support automatic code splitting.</item>
        <item>Tree shaking: remove dead exports. Requires ES module syntax (import/export); CommonJS (require) prevents static analysis.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="antipatterns">
      <rule>
        <statement>Profile before optimizing. Agents will refactor cold paths because they look messy; always demand an APM trace or flame graph identifying the hot path before accepting a performance change proposal.</statement>
        <rationale>Cold-path refactoring wastes engineering cycles and introduces risk with no latency benefit. Hot paths are identified by sampling, not by reading code.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>N+1 Queries — detection: ORM query log shows one query per loop iteration (1 list query + N detail queries). Fix: eager loading (JOIN, prefetch_related in Django, includes in ActiveRecord, DataLoader in GraphQL). Typical improvement: 100 items = 101 queries → 2 queries.</item>
        <item>Sync External Calls — detection: APM traces show thread blocked on outbound HTTP/gRPC with no async context. Fix: async/await, connection pools, circuit breakers with timeouts. Return 202 Accepted and process async for non-blocking user flow.</item>
        <item>No Caching — detection: cache hit ratio &lt; 60% on hot paths, or cache layer absent entirely. Fix: add multi-layer caching per caching-architecture methodology.</item>
        <item>Over-Fetching — detection: response payload contains columns never read by the caller; API returns full objects when only IDs are needed. Fix: field selection (GraphQL), pagination (cursor or offset), API versioning to add selective endpoints.</item>
        <item>No Connection Pooling — detection: DB connection count grows with request concurrency, TLS handshake time visible in traces, "too many connections" errors under load. Fix: PgBouncer (PostgreSQL), ProxySQL (MySQL), SQLAlchemy pool, HikariCP (Java). Size per formula: core_count × 2.</item>
        <item>Large Payloads — detection: network transfer time dominates trace waterfall; payload &gt; 100KB in a typical API response. Fix: pagination (default 20–100 items), Brotli/gzip compression, binary serialization (Protobuf, MessagePack) for internal APIs.</item>
        <item>Missing Indexes — detection: EXPLAIN ANALYZE shows Seq Scan on large tables; pg_stat_user_tables.seq_scan rising. Fix: index columns in WHERE and JOIN ON clauses, index foreign keys, add partial/covering indexes for hot queries.</item>
        <item>Premature Optimization — detection: team spends time micro-benchmarking cold code, introducing complexity without a measured performance problem. Fix: measure first (APM baseline + load test), optimize only paths appearing in the 80th percentile of trace spans.</item>
      </list>
      <list>
        <item>Step 1 — APM dashboards: identify slow endpoints (Datadog, Grafana Tempo, New Relic, Honeycomb). Filter to p95 and p99, not mean.</item>
        <item>Step 2 — Distributed traces: find the slow span within the slowest endpoint. Attribute to one layer (DB, external call, CPU).</item>
        <item>Step 3 — Flame graphs: for CPU-attributed spans, use py-spy (Python), async-profiler (JVM), or pprof (Go) to identify the hot function.</item>
        <item>Step 4 — Database profiling: EXPLAIN ANALYZE (PostgreSQL), slow query log (MySQL), pg_stat_statements for aggregate patterns.</item>
        <item>Step 5 — Network analysis: if network contributes &gt;20% of trace, check compression, payload size, and CDN cache hit ratio.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>Run a measurement-first loop: a profiler-agent (reads APM/traces), an analyzer-agent (identifies bottleneck layer), a designer-agent (proposes change with predicted impact), and a validator-agent (defines and runs the load test that proves/disproves the prediction). Always require the predicted improvement number in the change proposal so the validator has a falsification target. Iterate until SLOs hold under target load.</p>
      <prompt purpose="bottleneck-identification"><![CDATA[
INPUT: APM traces + flamegraph + slow query log.
TASK: Identify the dominant bottleneck layer (client/CDN/LB/app/data).
OUTPUT: One layer, one root cause, one proposed change with predicted
p95 improvement (ms) and predicted cost delta. No hand-waving.
      ]]></prompt>
      <prompt purpose="load-test-validator"><![CDATA[
ROLE: load-test-validator
INPUT: change proposal with predicted p95 improvement.
TASK: Generate a k6/vegeta script reproducing the production traffic mix
(reads/writes ratio, key skew, RPS profile). Output a pass/fail criterion
based on the prediction. Run it. Report.
      ]]></prompt>
    </section>

    <section name="ai-agent-gotchas">
      <list>
        <item>Agents conflate throughput and latency; force the prompt to talk about both per change.</item>
        <item>LLM-suggested optimizations frequently change algorithmic complexity without measurement; require Big-O before/after.</item>
        <item>Auto-scaling recommendations skip cold-start cost; demand cold-start latency in the proposal.</item>
        <item>Database "add an index" suggestions ignore write amplification; require a write-cost estimate.</item>
        <item>Human-in-loop gates: SLO sign-off, capacity plan review, post-deploy SLO review at 24h and 7d.</item>
        <item>Cache hit ratios, DB connection pool saturation, GC pauses, and TLS handshake counts are the four metrics agents miss most often — name them explicitly in the prompt.</item>
        <item>Agents conflate throughput and latency — a change that improves throughput (batch processing) often increases individual p95 latency. Require both metrics per change proposal.</item>
        <item>LLM optimization suggestions frequently change algorithmic complexity without measurement; require Big-O before/after and a load test proving the improvement.</item>
        <item>"Add an index" suggestions ignore write amplification: each additional index adds overhead to every INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE. Require a write-cost estimate alongside the read benefit.</item>
        <item>Auto-scaling recommendations skip cold-start latency cost; demand pod startup time in the proposal and pre-scaling strategy for known traffic spikes.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="tools">
      <list>
        <item>k6 — Modern load testing, JS scripts. https://k6.io/</item>
        <item>vegeta — HTTP load generator with histograms. https://github.com/tsenart/vegeta</item>
        <item>wrk / wrk2 — Constant-throughput load tests. https://github.com/giltene/wrk2</item>
        <item>locust — Python-driven load testing. https://locust.io/</item>
        <item>hey — Simple HTTP benchmark. go install github.com/rakyll/hey</item>
        <item>pyroscope / parca — Continuous profiling. https://pyroscope.io/ / https://parca.dev/</item>
        <item>pprof / async-profiler — Language-specific profiling (per-language).</item>
        <item>pgBadger / pg_stat_statements — PostgreSQL slow query analysis. https://github.com/darold/pgbadger</item>
        <item>siege — Legacy but still useful HTTP stress. https://github.com/JoeDog/siege</item>
        <item>Lighthouse CI — Frontend perf budgets in CI. npm i -g @lhci/cli</item>
        <item>Datadog APM — SaaS, strong API, trace-driven analysis.</item>
        <item>Grafana Cloud / Tempo / Mimir — SaaS+OSS, OTEL-native, queryable via PromQL/LogQL/TraceQL.</item>
        <item>New Relic — SaaS, NRQL queries good for agent loops.</item>
        <item>Honeycomb — SaaS, high-cardinality tracing; great for agent analysis.</item>
        <item>k6 Cloud / Grafana Cloud k6 — SaaS, persisted load tests with diff.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/k6-load-test.js" purpose="k6 script with steady + spike scenarios, p95/p99 thresholds, and randomized key distribution."/>
    </templates>

